- **Commit often**: Don't wait until feature is complete
- **Meaningful commits**: Each commit should be meaningful and reviewable

## Best Practices

### DO

- ‚úÖ Write clear, descriptive commit messages
- ‚úÖ Use Conventional Commits format
- ‚úÖ Reference issues in commit messages
- ‚úÖ Keep commits small and focused
- ‚úÖ Test before committing
- ‚úÖ Sync with main regularly
- ‚úÖ Review your own commits before pushing

### DON'T

- ‚ùå Commit directly to `main` branch
- ‚ùå Write vague commit messages
- ‚ùå Commit broken code
- ‚ùå Commit large, unrelated changes together
- ‚ùå Force push to `main`
- ‚ùå Skip pre-commit hooks (if configured)
- ‚ùå Commit secrets or credentials

## Pre-commit Hooks (If Configured)

If using Husky or similar:

- Run linting on staged files
- Run formatting on staged files
- Run type checking
- Prevent commits with errors

## Merge Strategies

### Squash and Merge (Recommended)

- Combines all commits into a single commit
- Cleaner git history
- Easier to revert if needed
- Use for feature branches

### Merge Commit

- Preserves individual commit history
- Use when commit history is important
- Creates merge commit in history

### Rebase and Merge

- Linear history without merge commits
- Use when you want completely linear history
- Can be more complex for reviewers

